01:33.790 --> 01:36.230
- ESTHER: Harry?
- It's all right, Esther.

01:37.350 --> 01:39.111
I can't sleep.

02:00.794 --> 02:03.954
<i>HARRY: There is a story
about the Greek gods.</i>

02:04.994 --> 02:09.275
<i>They were bored,
so they invented human beings,</i>

02:09.315 --> 02:13.075
<i>but they were still bored,
so they invented love.</i>

02:14.035 --> 02:16.356
<i>Then they weren't bored any longer,</i>

02:16.436 --> 02:20.317
<i>so they decided to try love
for themselves.</i>

02:21.637 --> 02:25.198
<i>And finally they invented laughter,</i>

02:26.718 --> 02:28.718
<i>so they could stand it.</i>

02:52.602 --> 02:53.682
(INDISTINCT CHATTERING)

02:55.682 --> 02:57.562
(CHEERING)

02:58.122 --> 03:00.443
- Harry!
- HARRY: Bradley?

03:00.483 --> 03:02.003
What are you doing away from Jitters?

03:02.083 --> 03:04.803
I just took the afternoon off. I...

03:04.883 --> 03:07.644
My wife's got a softball game
out here today.

03:07.684 --> 03:08.684
Ah.

03:08.764 --> 03:09.964
Honey?

03:10.044 --> 03:12.564
Hey, I'd like you to meet
Professor Stevenson.

03:12.844 --> 03:14.685
Harry, this is Kathryn.

03:14.725 --> 03:16.285
- Nice to meet you.
- Nice to meet you.

03:16.325 --> 03:18.365
He's a... He's a regular over at the shop.

03:18.405 --> 03:19.445
(CROWD CHEERING)

03:19.525 --> 03:21.766
WOMAN: Take her down!
One more! One more!

03:22.246 --> 03:25.726
- HARRY: She seems very determined.
- (CHUCKLING) You have no idea.

03:26.806 --> 03:28.567
BRADLEY: Wait for your pitch, sweetie.

03:29.287 --> 03:30.287
Yeah!

03:30.367 --> 03:33.207
- There it is! There it is! Okay, take two!
- JENNY: Gray! Melissa!

03:33.287 --> 03:35.407
- BRADLEY: There you go!
- Right here.

03:36.488 --> 03:37.448
BRADLEY: Yeah!

03:37.528 --> 03:38.528
(BRADLEY WHOOPING)

03:38.568 --> 03:40.248
Don't even think about it.

03:41.328 --> 03:42.528
Not bad, huh?

03:42.608 --> 03:44.329
- Not bad.
- Yeah, yeah, yeah!

03:44.969 --> 03:47.289
BRADLEY: Take the lead. Go! Go!

03:48.529 --> 03:49.489
(KATHRYN GRUNTS)

03:49.849 --> 03:51.131
(CROWD SIGHING)

03:51.251 --> 03:52.451
WOMAN: Nice save out there.

03:52.531 --> 03:54.291
Don't say I didn't warn you.

03:55.051 --> 03:56.731
(CROWD CHEERING)

04:02.292 --> 04:04.932
(ALL WHOOPING)

04:05.013 --> 04:07.493
(CHATTERING)

04:16.293 --> 04:17.934
I'm sorry about it.

04:18.014 --> 04:20.135
No. Well, that's true, though.
Answer me this.

04:20.214 --> 04:22.335
If your sport's
suddenly being taken seriously,

04:22.415 --> 04:25.135
how come we're wearing long pants
and you guys are still wearing shorts?

04:25.215 --> 04:26.855
Because we're hot.

04:28.096 --> 04:29.176
Oh!

04:29.256 --> 04:30.216
Hmm!

04:30.376 --> 04:32.696
- Hey, that was a great play.
- Thank you.

04:32.776 --> 04:34.096
Join us. Sit down.

04:35.137 --> 04:37.057
- Yeah.
- Why not?

04:37.377 --> 04:39.777
It was really good. Very athletic.

04:39.857 --> 04:42.778
- Hey, I'm Jenny.
- Hi. Kathryn.

04:42.858 --> 04:46.338
- Nice to meet you.
- Hi. Bradley Smith. I'm her other half.

04:47.018 --> 04:48.298
And this is Harry Stevenson.

04:48.338 --> 04:50.139
- Hi.
- Nice to meet you.

04:50.939 --> 04:52.819
How long have you guys been married?

04:52.859 --> 04:55.939
- Almost...
- Six years and a little bit of change.

04:58.940 --> 05:01.100
You know, I think I'm going to go
put some money in that jukebox.

05:01.180 --> 05:03.300
Will you save my spot for me?

05:03.380 --> 05:04.661
- Yeah.
- Yeah.

05:05.501 --> 05:06.501
Oh.

05:06.581 --> 05:08.461
BRADLEY: Anyway, I mean,
I could tell you one thing, they...

05:08.501 --> 05:10.421
They take the game seriously.

05:10.501 --> 05:13.302
I mean, they're practicing
three nights a week.

05:13.422 --> 05:16.062
HARRY: Well, that's how you get it done.
BRADLEY: Yeah?

05:16.342 --> 05:19.223
HARRY: If you'd studied that hard, Bradley,
you might have been a decent student.

05:19.263 --> 05:20.223
I agree.

05:20.463 --> 05:22.664
<i>(TURN PLAYING)</i>

05:24.144 --> 05:26.665
(INDISTINCT CHATTERING)

05:26.745 --> 05:28.665
<i>I want to see</i>

05:28.745 --> 05:30.225
- Hi.
- Hi.

05:30.265 --> 05:31.905
<i>what people saw</i>

05:32.625 --> 05:33.586
<i>I want to feel</i>

05:33.666 --> 05:34.626
(WHISPERING) Hi.

05:35.706 --> 05:38.786
<i>Like I felt before</i>

05:39.306 --> 05:43.187
<i>I want to see
the kingdom come</i>

05:43.267 --> 05:44.547
Excuse me. Thank you.

05:44.667 --> 05:46.147
<i>I want to feel</i>

05:46.227 --> 05:48.228
Yeah, well, thank you.

05:48.508 --> 05:50.068
<i>Forever young</i>

05:50.108 --> 05:52.028
You hear that song?

05:53.148 --> 05:56.269
That song goes out
from Jenny to Kathryn.

05:56.349 --> 05:58.629
From now on, that'll be our song.

05:58.869 --> 06:03.830
<i>I want to live in a world
where I belong</i>

06:03.950 --> 06:07.990
<i>I want to live</i>

06:08.230 --> 06:12.151
555-2189.

06:12.671 --> 06:17.071
<i>And I believe that
it won't be very long</i>

06:18.352 --> 06:20.672
<i>If we turn, turn</i>

06:25.473 --> 06:27.233
- ESTHER: Harry?
- Hey.

06:28.873 --> 06:31.513
How was your walk? Did I miss anything?

06:32.153 --> 06:35.914
A cool breeze, softball game,

06:35.994 --> 06:38.154
and two women falling in love.

06:39.955 --> 06:43.395
- With each other?
- And one of them is married.

06:43.475 --> 06:46.395
Funny thing is, nobody noticed.

06:47.075 --> 06:49.436
Not even the husband, two feet away.

06:49.476 --> 06:50.436
(CHUCKLES)

06:50.636 --> 06:54.077
- I'm sorry I missed that.
- I imagine he will be, too.

06:56.038 --> 06:58.078
His name is Bradley Smith.

06:59.438 --> 07:01.398
Went to school with Aaron.

07:06.679 --> 07:09.119
(SOFT MUSIC PLAYING ON STEREO)

07:21.481 --> 07:24.041
- Good morning, Professor.
- Oscar.

07:30.522 --> 07:31.803
Where's Bradley?

07:31.883 --> 07:34.443
He called in.
Said he'll be a little late this morning.

07:34.843 --> 07:36.323
- No peeking.
- No peeking.

07:36.363 --> 07:38.523
All right. Here we go. Ready?

07:41.164 --> 07:42.244
(DOGS BARKING)

07:46.445 --> 07:49.325
Oh, God. Forget it! No way!
There is no way that I'm going in there!

07:49.405 --> 07:51.805
Honey, honey...
Honey, this is really important.

07:51.885 --> 07:53.485
Why are you doing this to me?

07:53.565 --> 07:55.126
Because you can't go through
your entire life

07:55.206 --> 07:57.486
being afraid of little puppies.

07:57.566 --> 07:59.726
Yes, I can! I hate dogs. They bite.

07:59.806 --> 08:00.967
No, no, no, no.
They're not gonna bite you.

08:01.047 --> 08:03.767
They're in little cages. I promise.

08:03.847 --> 08:05.767
- I don't care.
- Okay. Okay.

08:05.807 --> 08:10.248
Look, just take a... Take a step.

08:10.288 --> 08:13.728
We'll just go in. We'll check it out.
If you get nervous, we'll come right back.

08:14.088 --> 08:16.369
(DOGS BARKING)

08:20.209 --> 08:21.169
Hmm?

08:22.209 --> 08:28.131
Look. See how adorable they are?

08:29.851 --> 08:31.252
Say hi.

08:32.172 --> 08:34.652
Hello... Otis.

08:36.092 --> 08:37.491
"Otis"?

08:38.653 --> 08:41.092
You know, he just looks like an Otis.

08:41.653 --> 08:42.613
Oh.

08:43.053 --> 08:45.814
Hi, Sophie. Aren't you a pretty girl?

08:46.774 --> 08:47.734
(CHUCKLES)

08:49.294 --> 08:53.175
Hey, Gordon, don't be sad.
Somebody's gonna pick you, okay?

08:55.335 --> 08:57.295
Randolph needs a haircut.

08:59.055 --> 09:00.216
(DOG WHIMPERING)

09:00.576 --> 09:02.016
And this one...

09:03.536 --> 09:05.016
This one is Bradley.

09:05.976 --> 09:08.377
Bradley, meet Bradley.

09:11.657 --> 09:14.738
And she was right. This dog, Harry,

09:15.858 --> 09:19.938
it looks exactly like me.

09:20.018 --> 09:22.379
Didn't you tell me
your wife was afraid of dogs?

09:22.459 --> 09:25.619
No, no, no. Not anymore. I mean, she...
I cured her.

09:26.099 --> 09:30.300
See, I think Kathryn was trying
to send me a subliminal message.

09:30.380 --> 09:34.140
I think she was telling me
that she wanted that dog,

09:34.180 --> 09:37.341
the dog, Harry,
the dog she named after me,

09:37.421 --> 09:41.421
as a gift. Maybe for her birthday.

09:42.661 --> 09:45.622
In fact, I know it. What do you think?

09:45.662 --> 09:49.702
- I think I'd proceed with caution.
- No, you don't understand. We need a dog.

09:49.782 --> 09:51.222
I have been telling her
we should have a baby.

09:51.302 --> 09:53.784
She's the one who keeps saying
she's not ready.

09:53.824 --> 09:58.184
Bradley, if you get the dog,

09:58.264 --> 10:02.105
you're telling her that you know her
better than she knows herself.

10:02.145 --> 10:03.185
So?

10:03.625 --> 10:06.466
So, you better be right.

10:11.666 --> 10:15.707
BRADLEY: You know what I feel like doing?
I feel like just driving over there

10:15.787 --> 10:18.147
and grabbing the little guy
before somebody else gets him.

10:18.187 --> 10:20.187
So just do it, though, you know? Go for it.

10:20.267 --> 10:21.308
Yeah? You think?

10:21.348 --> 10:22.788
You only live once.

10:22.868 --> 10:24.308
Probably.

10:24.388 --> 10:25.308
Harry?

10:25.388 --> 10:27.868
Why are you asking me, Bradley?
Your mind's made up.

10:27.908 --> 10:29.589
Well, not entirely.

10:32.389 --> 10:35.870
- Hey, you need anybody to work here?
- Yes! Yeah.

10:36.590 --> 10:39.110
I mean, if that's all right with you.

10:41.430 --> 10:42.550
You...

10:43.471 --> 10:46.031
You have any experience
with this kind of work?

10:46.111 --> 10:48.191
- No.
- OSCAR: Neither did I when I started.

10:48.231 --> 10:50.992
- Do you like coffee?
- Not much.

10:51.432 --> 10:53.312
OSCAR: She'll learn to love it.

10:54.152 --> 10:55.392
But why here?

10:56.312 --> 10:57.312
I don't know.

10:57.392 --> 10:59.793
I just kind of felt
a harmonic convergence in this place.

10:59.873 --> 11:02.873
She's right, you know?
I felt the same kind of thing.

11:04.753 --> 11:05.794
Ah.

11:05.834 --> 11:06.794
HARRY: Bradley.

11:09.074 --> 11:12.995
I think you'd better hire the girl
or you're going to lose Oscar.

11:13.035 --> 11:14.115
And if you lose Oscar,

11:14.195 --> 11:16.995
you're never gonna make it to the
Humane Society in time to get the dog.

11:17.035 --> 11:18.955
Good point. You're hired.

11:19.755 --> 11:21.756
Man the fort. Keys!

11:21.996 --> 11:23.276
Thank you.

11:24.237 --> 11:26.277
(CELL PHONE RINGING)

11:30.998 --> 11:32.078
Hello?

11:34.238 --> 11:35.239
Hi.

11:37.239 --> 11:40.159
<i>HARRY: Sometimes you don't know
you've crossed a line</i>

11:40.239 --> 11:42.280
<i>until you're already on the other side.</i>

11:42.320 --> 11:43.960
- Hey.
- Hi.

11:44.040 --> 11:44.960
Thanks.

11:45.040 --> 11:47.920
<i>HARRY: Of course,
by then it's too late.</i>

11:47.960 --> 11:49.641
- You good?
- Yeah.

11:49.681 --> 11:50.961
All right.

11:58.642 --> 12:00.482
Don't be nervous, okay?

12:01.362 --> 12:02.962
Who says I'm nervous?

12:03.362 --> 12:05.243
It must be pretty weird
to be married and straight,

12:05.323 --> 12:08.043
and suddenly
you're thinking about a woman.

12:09.963 --> 12:11.603
Yeah, well.

12:11.684 --> 12:15.564
- Who said anything about...
- It's right there. It's in your eyes.

12:16.404 --> 12:18.444
Big, beautiful, hazel eyes.

12:19.925 --> 12:22.605
Oh, man, we're going to have adventures,
you and me.

12:22.645 --> 12:25.045
It's going to be, like, Kathryn and Jenny.

12:26.405 --> 12:27.966
Jenny and Kathryn.

12:39.487 --> 12:42.288
- Name?
- Chloe.

12:42.328 --> 12:44.448
- Barlow.
- "Chloe"?

12:46.128 --> 12:49.649
It used to be plain old Chloe,
but I customized it.

12:49.689 --> 12:51.129
- Really?
- Yeah.

12:51.689 --> 12:53.849
Well, you know, Chloe...

12:54.969 --> 12:59.851
You're really pretty.
Has anybody ever told you that?

12:59.931 --> 13:04.092
I think I scare guys off
because I'm so intense.

13:04.172 --> 13:07.252
Well, you don't have to worry about me
in that department.

13:08.212 --> 13:09.852
- Really?
- Really.

13:10.012 --> 13:10.933
Uh-huh?

13:13.653 --> 13:15.773
That's the second time this week.

13:15.853 --> 13:16.813
(CHUCKLING)

13:17.093 --> 13:19.054
Yeah, what are the odds?

13:19.494 --> 13:20.614
Not two women again?

13:20.694 --> 13:22.974
No, more conventional this time.

13:23.054 --> 13:25.855
Classical, in fact, like Romeo and Juliet.

13:26.695 --> 13:30.015
They laid eyes on each other
and their fates were sealed.

13:30.335 --> 13:33.496
Life will never be the same
for either one of them again.

13:33.536 --> 13:36.216
Now, don't you go
falling in love at first sight.

13:37.896 --> 13:40.257
Too late, my dear. I already did.

13:41.497 --> 13:43.777
Did you talk to the dean today?

13:48.258 --> 13:50.458
If you're going to go back
to teaching next semester,

13:50.498 --> 13:52.218
you've got to let him know.

13:52.298 --> 13:53.458
Esther...

13:56.219 --> 13:57.819
I'm aware of that.

14:04.260 --> 14:06.260
(SOFT JAZZ PLAYING ON STEREO)

14:15.101 --> 14:18.702
You know how every relationship has, like,
a perfect day?

14:19.782 --> 14:20.822
Yeah.

14:24.262 --> 14:26.224
What do you mean?

14:26.304 --> 14:29.824
It's just this day

14:30.864 --> 14:32.545
and you look back years later

14:32.585 --> 14:35.505
and it stands out from all the rest,
you know?

14:36.225 --> 14:39.266
Not because you won the lottery
or anything, just...

14:40.346 --> 14:45.186
Just an average day, but somehow...
You know, perfect.

14:47.307 --> 14:49.027
Today's like that.

14:54.388 --> 14:56.068
(CELL PHONE RINGING)

14:57.908 --> 15:00.868
Excuse me. Hey. Hello.

15:09.390 --> 15:11.590
(WHISPERING) Yeah, I know. Me too.

15:24.912 --> 15:26.552
This should be interesting.

15:26.632 --> 15:28.432
- Please, Aggie.
- Bradley.

15:28.512 --> 15:30.953
I only need you to keep him till Friday,
Kathryn's birthday.

15:31.033 --> 15:33.993
- Kathryn is scared of dogs.
- Not anymore.

15:34.073 --> 15:35.673
- I took her to the pound.
- But...

15:35.753 --> 15:37.713
Besides, isn't that
what relationships are all about?

15:37.793 --> 15:39.394
Overcoming your deepest fears?

15:39.474 --> 15:42.954
- His name is Bradley Jr.
- Did you think of that one all by yourself?

15:43.034 --> 15:44.234
No, smartass.

15:44.274 --> 15:46.635
Billy, your Uncle Bradley's here!
He brought along a friend.

15:46.675 --> 15:50.035
- I'm gonna miss you. Here you go.
- Oh, God. Oh, God.

15:51.715 --> 15:53.596
- Only until Friday.
- Yeah.

15:54.036 --> 15:55.196
He likes you.

16:21.280 --> 16:23.201
Well, would you look at that?

16:23.801 --> 16:27.281
They have completely moved out,
hammock and everything.

16:27.801 --> 16:30.162
You never heard such screaming.

16:30.202 --> 16:32.202
The movers told them to shut the hell up

16:32.282 --> 16:35.242
or they'd throw
all their things in the street.

16:38.803 --> 16:40.963
Remember when they first moved in here?

16:41.043 --> 16:42.963
I said I'd never seen a happier couple.

16:43.003 --> 16:44.523
What did I tell you?

16:44.924 --> 16:47.844
It's the house. It's cursed.

16:49.244 --> 16:52.325
Houses aren't cursed, now. People are.

17:04.445 --> 17:06.205
You're a jock, huh?

17:06.286 --> 17:07.567
I used to be.

17:08.047 --> 17:09.887
That was a long time ago.

17:11.327 --> 17:14.647
That's my mom.
She took off when I was in junior high.

17:15.808 --> 17:17.728
Bat drove her away.

17:17.808 --> 17:20.887
- Bat?
- My dad. His name's Bathold.

17:21.489 --> 17:25.049
People call him the Bat, so that ought
to tell you something, right?

17:26.249 --> 17:28.290
Yeah, he blows up tree stumps for a living.

17:28.369 --> 17:31.171
Then he comes home,
thinks about my mom,

17:31.251 --> 17:33.011
and gets shitfaced.

17:41.932 --> 17:43.132
Yours?

17:43.212 --> 17:44.253
Yeah.

17:44.293 --> 17:47.133
My mom gave it to me when I was a kid.

17:47.573 --> 17:49.613
Do you sleep with him?

17:50.013 --> 17:54.694
Yeah. What? Is that bad?
He's a great little spoon.

17:56.894 --> 18:00.695
Ex-jock druggie
who still has a teddy bear?

18:01.415 --> 18:03.055
Nothing hotter than that.

18:03.975 --> 18:06.496
And what makes you think I'm a druggie?

18:07.016 --> 18:09.656
Pisces, Virgo rising.

18:10.456 --> 18:12.976
What was it? Coke?

18:15.697 --> 18:16.657
E?

18:18.457 --> 18:19.737
Heroin?

18:20.177 --> 18:21.698
Sure, why not?

18:25.098 --> 18:27.258
So, why'd you quit?

18:27.819 --> 18:29.699
What makes you think I quit?

18:32.299 --> 18:36.420
Oh, right. Pisces, Virgo rising.

18:36.940 --> 18:38.220
Very good.

18:42.541 --> 18:46.701
I had this dream one night
while I was wasted.

18:46.781 --> 18:52.502
There was this African monkey
whispering all this creepy shit in my ear.

18:53.582 --> 18:57.983
He said that if I didn't get clean
I was gonna die young,

18:59.064 --> 19:02.624
OD in an alleyway on a pile of garbage.

19:06.505 --> 19:12.306
And that morning I woke up
and I went to my first meeting.

19:14.546 --> 19:18.426
It was seven months and two weeks ago.

19:20.187 --> 19:25.067
I can prove it. I got my six-month chip.

19:31.508 --> 19:32.948
Cool.

19:33.428 --> 19:35.109
It doesn't scare you?

19:37.429 --> 19:41.389
Most junkies, you know,
even if they never use again,

19:43.470 --> 19:45.910
it doesn't matter. It's too late.

19:47.510 --> 19:50.991
They're just gone,
you know, permanent zombies.

19:51.631 --> 19:55.471
But then there's junkies where
all the horrible places they've been,

19:56.872 --> 19:58.992
all the horrible shit they've done,

20:00.152 --> 20:02.952
the fact that they come back from it

20:03.592 --> 20:07.673
makes them better people
than if they'd never used in the first place.

20:11.474 --> 20:12.754
That's you.

20:35.838 --> 20:37.758
Hey, where's the little girl's room?

20:37.958 --> 20:39.158
Across the hall.

20:39.198 --> 20:40.358
Okay.

20:47.119 --> 20:48.080
(GASPS)

20:48.880 --> 20:49.960
Oh, shit!

20:50.040 --> 20:50.960
(BANGING ON DOOR)

20:51.040 --> 20:53.760
Oscar! Goddamn it!
You get that girl out of your room, Oscar!

20:53.840 --> 20:54.840
Get the fuck away!

20:54.880 --> 20:56.481
BAT: You do it right now, damn it!
Do you hear me?

20:56.561 --> 20:58.521
I should have warned you.
I didn't think he'd be back this early.

20:58.601 --> 21:00.441
BAT: Oscar! I ain't running
a motel around here!

21:00.481 --> 21:02.161
- You hear me?
- Yeah, I heard you!

21:02.241 --> 21:04.922
- Maybe we should just go out the window.
- No!

21:04.962 --> 21:06.842
We're going out the way we came in.

21:06.882 --> 21:08.602
- BAT: Oscar.
- You ready?

21:22.324 --> 21:23.484
Hello, missy.

21:23.564 --> 21:25.365
Pleased to meet you. The name's Chloe.

21:25.445 --> 21:28.205
Yeah, well, don't you come in this house
again unless I invite you.

21:28.285 --> 21:30.525
There'll be trouble
I can't be responsible for.

21:31.405 --> 21:32.846
BAT: You hear me?

21:38.406 --> 21:40.127
Hey, don't be scared, all right?

21:40.167 --> 21:43.767
He is a mean son of a bitch,
but I can be, too.

21:46.567 --> 21:48.808
I'll protect you from anything.

22:00.170 --> 22:02.131
Bradley, we have to talk.

22:02.411 --> 22:03.731
No, hold on.

22:12.892 --> 22:14.692
That's really sweet.

22:19.613 --> 22:21.613
Happy birthday, sweetheart.

22:24.614 --> 22:26.054
It's a dog.

22:27.854 --> 22:31.575
No. No, no. That's not... It's the dog.

22:31.655 --> 22:34.415
That's Bradley Jr.
That's the dog you picked out.

22:34.495 --> 22:37.215
But I hate dogs and you know that.

22:37.295 --> 22:39.896
No, you don't. You... You love dogs.

22:39.976 --> 22:43.536
I would have said anything
to get out of that room.

22:44.656 --> 22:47.657
I don't want a goddamn dog!

22:47.697 --> 22:51.497
And you know that, but you
got me one anyway, because you...

22:51.537 --> 22:55.258
- Okay. Okay, time out, Kathryn...
- Because you have no idea who I am.

22:55.338 --> 23:00.298
I mean, I might as well be invisible to you.
What color are my eyes, Bradley?

23:00.338 --> 23:02.899
- What?
- Yeah, what color are my eyes?

23:04.659 --> 23:06.899
- Green!
- Hazel!

23:06.979 --> 23:10.780
My eyes are hazel! I mean, Christ!
You're an artist!

23:10.860 --> 23:13.420
Okay, but there's a little greenish,
hazel tint.

23:13.460 --> 23:15.381
All right, listen,
we're rushing the dog thing.

23:15.461 --> 23:16.421
- You're right.
- No.

23:16.501 --> 23:19.221
No, it's not just the dog thing
or the eye thing. It's everything.

23:19.301 --> 23:22.581
It's every goddamn thing!
I cannot do this for one more day!

23:22.661 --> 23:24.822
- It's like I don't even exist!
- What? You're leaving?

23:24.902 --> 23:27.622
- Oh, so now you don't miss a thing.
- Where are you going with this?

23:27.702 --> 23:30.984
You know the shortstop,
the one that you asked over to our table?

23:31.064 --> 23:33.864
Yes! She tagged you out.

23:34.144 --> 23:38.105
Yeah, well,
I'm not the only one she tagged out.

23:38.185 --> 23:39.305
But you wouldn't know that,

23:39.385 --> 23:41.345
because you have your
head so far up your ass.

23:41.425 --> 23:43.865
Wait, you... You're friends with her?

23:47.426 --> 23:49.986
Wow. Goodbye, Bradley.

24:00.188 --> 24:02.988
If Kathryn's meant to be with women,
so be it,

24:03.948 --> 24:07.829
but I just can't help but think
maybe I did something to cause it.

24:08.909 --> 24:09.869
Mmm?

24:10.349 --> 24:12.429
To put her off men forever.

24:14.910 --> 24:19.030
But what? Never cheated.

24:20.350 --> 24:21.751
I didn't lie.

24:23.791 --> 24:26.311
I made love to her on a regular basis.

24:37.913 --> 24:40.233
She fell in love, that's all.

24:41.993 --> 24:43.193
One minute she was married,

24:43.273 --> 24:45.514
next minute there was this person
right in front of her,

24:45.594 --> 24:48.954
whom she couldn't ignore
no matter how hard she tried.

24:50.314 --> 24:52.195
How do you know that?

24:52.235 --> 24:56.635
Well, I was there when they met.
So were you.

24:59.036 --> 25:02.717
Bradley, look.
Try focusing on simple pleasures.

25:03.077 --> 25:05.237
You know? Small blessings.

25:06.438 --> 25:07.398
Hmm.

25:07.478 --> 25:09.038
Like... Like what?

25:11.078 --> 25:12.998
That's not for me to say.

25:14.639 --> 25:17.479
- I got my hair, right, Harry?
- There's a start.

25:17.559 --> 25:18.639
Okay.

25:20.719 --> 25:21.680
Well...

25:22.760 --> 25:27.000
- I got this place.
- Best espresso in Portland. The best!

25:28.281 --> 25:31.201
- I got my little dog.
- A loyal companion.

25:31.761 --> 25:33.321
I'm really sorry, Bradley,

25:33.401 --> 25:36.802
but you can't have the dog back.
We're going to keep him.

25:37.642 --> 25:39.082
Agatha, that's my dog.

25:39.122 --> 25:40.802
Not anymore. He's bonded with us.

25:40.882 --> 25:42.282
- No...
- His name is Gumbo now.

25:42.362 --> 25:43.803
Wait! Wait. Wait.

25:45.163 --> 25:46.243
We had a deal.

25:46.283 --> 25:49.083
Well, that was then and this is now.
I'm so sorry, Bradley,

25:49.163 --> 25:50.123
(DOG BARKS)

25:50.203 --> 25:52.364
but Billy loves the dog
and we love the dog.

25:52.444 --> 25:55.324
Don't talk to me about love, okay?
My wife left me.

25:55.404 --> 25:57.444
- I know.
- Okay? For another woman.

25:57.484 --> 26:01.005
I'm alone, okay?
I want a dog. I need that dog!

26:01.085 --> 26:02.405
Brad... Bradley!

26:02.485 --> 26:05.366
My heart goes out to you, sweetie.
I think Kathryn is a selfish bitch.

26:05.446 --> 26:06.846
I think what you should do
is go straight to the pound

26:06.926 --> 26:09.766
- and pick yourself out another dog.
- We had a deal!

26:09.846 --> 26:13.567
I know. Well, I have to take it back.
It's null and void.

26:13.647 --> 26:16.247
Aggie, I need that dog, okay? Please. I...

26:16.327 --> 26:18.647
This is not a joke.
I'm talking about my stability, here.

26:18.727 --> 26:21.968
- I know. I'm really sorry, Bradley, but...
- No...

26:22.048 --> 26:25.608
As Billy's mother,
my responsibility is to him first, okay?

26:25.648 --> 26:27.409
- Good luck.
- No. No!

26:28.649 --> 26:29.769
Aggie!

26:29.849 --> 26:31.049
(DOG CONTINUES BARKING)

26:58.174 --> 26:59.134
(WHIMPERING)

27:03.734 --> 27:07.655
(WHISPERING) Hi, Bradley.
Hi. Oh, God. How you doing?

27:07.735 --> 27:08.735
Huh?

27:08.815 --> 27:11.215
I missed you. I missed you so much.

27:11.896 --> 27:13.656
Uncle Bradley?

27:13.736 --> 27:16.816
Hey, how you doing, Billy?
Come over here.

27:17.536 --> 27:19.457
Come on.

27:19.537 --> 27:21.577
I wanted to have a little talk with you.
How are you?

27:21.657 --> 27:23.977
- Mom's not here.
- No, I know. I know.

27:24.057 --> 27:27.578
I just... I don't know if you've heard or not,

27:27.658 --> 27:30.898
but your Aunt Kathryn

27:30.978 --> 27:36.019
has gone away to a place
where boys aren't allowed.

27:36.939 --> 27:40.299
And I'm all alone in the world, kiddo,
and I need...

27:40.379 --> 27:42.740
- I need Bradley Jr.
- Who?

27:44.300 --> 27:45.820
- Bonkers.
- Who's that?

27:45.900 --> 27:48.341
- Bingo, the dog. I need this dog.
- But he's mine.

27:48.421 --> 27:51.301
I know, I know, and someday,
when you get a little older,

27:51.381 --> 27:55.021
we're going to have a long conversation
about the nature of deals, you and I, okay?

27:55.101 --> 27:58.222
But I'll tell you what.
Right now, look at this.

27:58.302 --> 28:02.062
I want you to go buy yourself
a brand new dog.

28:02.142 --> 28:04.024
On me. Okay?

28:04.064 --> 28:06.264
But that's not enough.

28:06.304 --> 28:08.384
- Yeah, it is.
- No, it's not.

28:09.464 --> 28:12.025
It's... Okay, okay, okay.

28:13.305 --> 28:16.625
- You can buy a horse with that.
- It's still not enough.

28:17.345 --> 28:18.426
AGATHA: Billy?

28:18.786 --> 28:20.226
- Mom!
- Okay, okay.

28:20.306 --> 28:22.346
Is that Uncle Bradley's car?

28:22.426 --> 28:24.226
I'm keeping the leash.

28:27.067 --> 28:28.667
I'm taking this.

28:31.187 --> 28:33.588
<i>(HALLELUJAH PLAYING)</i>

28:39.909 --> 28:43.389
The newspaper said there was gonna be
a meteor shower tonight.

28:43.469 --> 28:44.589
So...

28:46.589 --> 28:49.790
I figured this would be the best place
to see it.

28:54.871 --> 28:58.831
Hey, you know how
when people are super rich,

28:58.911 --> 29:03.472
they got those hallways at the front
of the house, you know, by the front door?

29:03.552 --> 29:06.472
<i>OSCAR: And they put those
grandfather clocks there and...</i>

29:06.552 --> 29:10.513
- You mean like a foyer.
- Yes! Yes, like a foyer.

29:11.673 --> 29:15.033
All right. It's the future, okay?

29:15.113 --> 29:19.074
So picture this, Oscar of the future,

29:19.114 --> 29:24.875
and I'm heading home from whatever
cool thing it is that I decide to do.

29:24.955 --> 29:28.635
- Where am I?
- You? You're in the house.

29:29.515 --> 29:31.516
- We live together?
- Of course we live together.

29:31.596 --> 29:33.476
What do you think?

29:33.556 --> 29:36.397
- What kind of house?
- Big.

29:36.477 --> 29:40.238
I go get the mail out of the box,
and we've got these huge fucking bills.

29:40.278 --> 29:45.438
Never seen anything like it.
Dentist, mortgage, electricity...

29:45.518 --> 29:49.359
The guy, you know,
that looks at your eye when you can't...

29:49.439 --> 29:52.079
- The optometrist?
- Yeah, him. He's there.

29:52.159 --> 29:54.920
And you're in the foyer.

29:56.280 --> 29:59.480
And you look out the window
and you see me.

30:00.560 --> 30:02.241
See my face?

30:02.321 --> 30:04.801
- Yeah.
- Do I look scared?

30:05.801 --> 30:07.441
No. You look happy.

30:08.562 --> 30:10.282
You know why?

30:11.602 --> 30:13.802
Because I can pay those bills.

30:14.002 --> 30:19.123
We got tons of money
and I'm not scared of anything.

30:21.683 --> 30:24.364
All right, your turn.

30:26.644 --> 30:29.284
- My turn what?
- The future.

30:31.565 --> 30:36.245
- Close your eyes. What do you see?
- Okay.

30:38.566 --> 30:41.206
- Nothing.
- Just look.

30:45.447 --> 30:49.007
Okay, in the foyer, I see...

30:50.007 --> 30:51.407
A table...

30:52.527 --> 30:54.008
And...

30:55.128 --> 30:57.928
- A staircase.
- Excellent.

30:59.008 --> 31:00.689
I'm going up the stairs.

31:01.809 --> 31:03.529
Get to the top yet?

31:04.089 --> 31:05.330
Almost.

31:05.690 --> 31:07.611
What's up those stairs?

31:09.891 --> 31:11.891
Look, Oscar.

31:12.891 --> 31:14.371
Kids.

31:15.452 --> 31:17.652
So many kids I can't count.

31:19.092 --> 31:20.892
They're our kids.

31:22.012 --> 31:24.293
I was hoping you'd say that.

31:24.373 --> 31:27.013
- Really?
- I told you.

31:28.973 --> 31:30.974
I'm not scared of anything.

31:31.054 --> 31:36.614
<i>Hallelujah
Hallelujah</i>

31:37.935 --> 31:40.415
<i>Hallelujah</i>

31:41.455 --> 31:46.256
<i>Hallelujah</i>

31:53.817 --> 31:56.897
<i>HARRY: A man living alone
is a king of sorts.</i>

31:56.977 --> 32:01.178
<i>Unfortunately, his kingdom is small,
with very few comforts.</i>

32:01.218 --> 32:05.138
<i>Bradley looked up from his paper one day
and realized</i>

32:05.218 --> 32:07.259
<i>that no one burns for him.</i>

32:11.499 --> 32:15.340
(SIGHING) Harry, I really feel like it's time
for me to get on with my life, you know?

32:15.420 --> 32:20.340
- Put the past behind me.
- That's a positive step, my friend.

32:20.420 --> 32:22.101
- Yeah.
- I gotta go.

32:26.101 --> 32:27.301
(INAUDIBLE)

32:29.702 --> 32:31.782
- Hi.
- Hey.

32:31.862 --> 32:35.582
Can I have a coffee? Large, black, to go.

32:35.622 --> 32:37.104
Thanks.

32:41.104 --> 32:44.145
- I think I've seen you in here before.
- Probably.

32:46.505 --> 32:48.265
- Here you go.
- Thanks.

32:51.066 --> 32:54.186
- You looking to buy a house?
- Sell one, actually.

32:56.906 --> 32:58.507
What about you?

32:59.547 --> 33:00.867
What about me?

33:00.907 --> 33:03.627
You're not looking to buy a house,
are you?

33:05.468 --> 33:07.868
- Rent, maybe.
- Really?

33:09.868 --> 33:13.469
- Well, sit down.
- Okay.

33:14.509 --> 33:15.469
Um...

33:16.149 --> 33:18.069
How many bedrooms?

33:18.229 --> 33:19.189
Uh...

33:19.749 --> 33:24.030
Two. One for me,
and maybe one for a little studio.

33:24.110 --> 33:26.190
- I paint sometimes.
- Okay.

33:26.510 --> 33:28.191
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

33:28.311 --> 33:30.751
The place that I have right now
is actually perfect,

33:30.831 --> 33:33.671
except it's haunted

33:34.751 --> 33:36.552
by a woman.

33:37.952 --> 33:39.472
She's a lesbian.

33:40.912 --> 33:43.593
My ex-wife left me for another woman.

33:45.353 --> 33:46.633
Oh, I see.

33:46.753 --> 33:48.513
(ELECTRICITY CRACKLING)

33:48.633 --> 33:51.754
- Shit!
- No, we get this here. Hold on.

33:51.834 --> 33:54.194
- We get this a lot, actually.
- Yeah.

33:55.154 --> 33:57.835
They said this was going to be a big one,
but I didn't believe them.

33:57.915 --> 33:58.955
Yeah.

34:00.275 --> 34:03.795
- It looks like you've got that under control.
- You think?

34:04.836 --> 34:05.996
(LAUGHING)

34:07.157 --> 34:09.237
Do you mind if I smoke?

34:10.357 --> 34:11.476
No.

34:12.277 --> 34:13.358
Of course I did hear a rumor

34:13.438 --> 34:15.598
that those things are supposed to be
bad for your health.

34:15.678 --> 34:17.398
Not these. They're organic.

34:17.478 --> 34:19.879
Oh! Those are the ones that cure cancer.

34:20.279 --> 34:21.639
Exactly.

34:25.399 --> 34:27.560
Look at that. Brilliant.

34:27.639 --> 34:29.400
Not according to my ex.

34:29.480 --> 34:36.001
She said that I had my head
so far up my ass I never saw her.

34:37.801 --> 34:39.440
And was she right?

34:42.641 --> 34:44.202
I'm afraid so.

34:46.842 --> 34:48.683
So you're the honest type.

34:48.763 --> 34:49.842
To a fault.

34:54.603 --> 34:56.043
Diana Croce.

34:58.164 --> 35:00.524
I'm Bradley Smith.

35:00.604 --> 35:04.645
It's been really nice talking to you,
Bradley, but I gotta be somewhere.

35:07.925 --> 35:09.045
Call me.

35:14.486 --> 35:15.766
(MOANING)

35:26.768 --> 35:28.288
Yeah!

35:31.288 --> 35:32.728
DIANA: Oh, my God.

35:32.808 --> 35:37.289
David, this wine is excellent.
Do you want a glass?

35:39.370 --> 35:41.331
Well, that was quick.

35:42.691 --> 35:44.651
- Yeah.
- You gotta be somewhere?

35:44.731 --> 35:48.252
- Yeah, I gotta go. I'm sorry.
- What? You've got a meeting?

35:48.292 --> 35:50.812
Karen's car is in the shop.
I gotta pick up my son at swim practice.

35:50.892 --> 35:52.652
So, I've got about 10 minutes
to get across town.

35:52.732 --> 35:56.493
Listen. Tuesday. Noon.

35:56.773 --> 35:59.893
I will bring even better wine,
some lunch. I promise.

36:00.333 --> 36:01.973
I'm really sorry.

36:04.214 --> 36:07.054
- I can't do it.
- What do you mean?

36:09.374 --> 36:13.255
I have an appointment
to show somebody a house.

36:15.135 --> 36:16.815
- What? You can't change that?
- No, actually.

36:16.895 --> 36:22.216
It's this guy that I met, Bradley Smith.
Runs this little coffeehouse called Jitters.

36:22.296 --> 36:24.737
That's the only time he can make it.

36:29.897 --> 36:31.217
Okay.

36:34.378 --> 36:37.538
Well, I'll call you tomorrow. Bye.

36:40.139 --> 36:41.099
(SIGHS)

36:47.500 --> 36:49.380
Why did you say that?

36:50.420 --> 36:52.900
(TIRES SQUEALING)

36:56.661 --> 36:58.181
(BOTTLES CLINKING)

37:00.901 --> 37:01.822
(GRUNTS)

37:05.902 --> 37:07.582
(MUTTERING)

37:12.704 --> 37:14.864
Hey, Oscar, I want you to...

37:23.225 --> 37:25.386
Goddamn it!

37:27.186 --> 37:29.066
That fucking bitch!

37:52.349 --> 37:54.310
- Morning.
- Hey.

37:57.670 --> 38:00.791
Honey, this isn't working out.

38:00.871 --> 38:02.471
You guys are gonna have to find a place
of your own.

38:02.551 --> 38:03.791
Yeah.

38:04.871 --> 38:08.992
I'm working on it.
Nothing in here we can afford. I...

38:13.072 --> 38:16.393
Well, I know a way you and Oscar
can make some money.

38:19.673 --> 38:21.433
- Here you go.
- Thanks.

38:31.475 --> 38:32.755
Thank you.

38:37.155 --> 38:38.716
I need some advice.

38:39.036 --> 38:40.117
Sure.

38:42.237 --> 38:45.638
Well, Oscar and I have been given
a business opportunity.

38:45.998 --> 38:47.758
Really?

38:47.838 --> 38:53.039
And if we were to make this... tape,

38:54.479 --> 38:58.039
it's not like it's something
we don't do all the time anyway.

39:00.080 --> 39:03.840
We could make, like, a thousand bucks,
if, you know, people order it.

39:03.920 --> 39:07.281
Oh, they'll order it.
Blind people will order it.

39:09.641 --> 39:11.241
Should we do it?

39:12.321 --> 39:15.122
You haven't told me
what you think about it.

39:15.842 --> 39:18.482
<i>CHLOE: I think if we were doing it
just for the money</i>

39:18.562 --> 39:20.642
<i>it would definitely be wrong.</i>

39:24.283 --> 39:25.603
What is it?

39:29.684 --> 39:30.884
What's wrong?

39:31.684 --> 39:32.604
(SIGHS)

39:34.244 --> 39:36.805
A young girl asked me for advice today.

39:37.645 --> 39:40.245
She was trying to decide
if she and her boyfriend

39:40.325 --> 39:43.926
should make a pornographic movie.

39:45.966 --> 39:47.686
I hope you told her no.

39:48.646 --> 39:49.926
I didn't.

39:51.127 --> 39:54.487
No, I tried to give her a perspective.

39:55.607 --> 39:59.448
I asked her questions. All very Socratic.

40:00.488 --> 40:06.009
I let her make up her own mind.
The same way I spoke to Aaron.

40:07.609 --> 40:09.970
- Sweetheart...
- What if I hadn't?

40:12.890 --> 40:17.091
What if I'd taken a stronger stance?

40:18.171 --> 40:21.892
What if I'd just told him,
"Son, this is right. This is wrong"?

40:21.972 --> 40:23.932
I mean, he wasn't my student,
for God's sake.

40:24.012 --> 40:25.492
He was my son.

40:34.613 --> 40:36.294
ESTHER: Look at me.

40:37.854 --> 40:39.294
Harry, please.

40:41.174 --> 40:44.775
You were a wonderful father. Nothing...

40:46.255 --> 40:49.095
Nothing that you could have done
would have stopped him.

40:49.135 --> 40:50.896
You don't know that.

40:51.696 --> 40:54.216
We don't know
what might have happened.

40:56.336 --> 40:57.497
Do we?

41:01.937 --> 41:03.337
Oh, Harry.

41:13.979 --> 41:15.899
DIANA: You like it?
BRADLEY: Yeah!

41:16.579 --> 41:19.339
It's pretty much
exactly what you asked for, Bradley.

41:19.379 --> 41:22.140
One bedroom plus a studio.

41:22.860 --> 41:25.420
But the important thing to remember
about this place is...

41:25.500 --> 41:28.901
The important thing
is whether or not you had fun last night.

41:28.981 --> 41:32.061
- Yes, I had a good time.
- What's that, Diana?

41:32.141 --> 41:36.662
- We always have a good time together.
- How come you never got married?

41:37.502 --> 41:40.062
Can we just stay on track here, Bradley,
for a minute?

41:40.142 --> 41:42.144
The owner will take a second mortgage,

41:42.224 --> 41:43.504
which means
that you can get out of renting...

41:43.584 --> 41:46.704
Is it because you never met anybody
as lovable as me?

41:47.904 --> 41:51.465
Are you ever going to buy a house,
or are you just jerking my chain?

41:55.865 --> 41:57.386
It's perfect.

42:00.586 --> 42:01.906
Really.

42:04.307 --> 42:05.707
I'll take it.

42:07.627 --> 42:09.187
Are you serious?

42:09.627 --> 42:12.148
Oh, my God,
I'm actually going to buy a house!

42:14.148 --> 42:17.708
I love this place, really.
It's perfect for you. It is.

42:17.988 --> 42:19.349
<i>Words fall through me</i>

42:19.389 --> 42:22.389
<i>And always fool me</i>

42:22.469 --> 42:26.310
<i>And I can't react</i>

